text.Taxonomy and naming:
Eucalyptus pruinosa was first formally described in 1843 by Johannes Conrad Schauer in Walper's book Repertorium Botanices Systematicae. The type specimen was collected by Robert Brown and Ferdinand Bauer from the South Wellesley Islands in the Gulf of Carpentaria off Queensland in 1802. The species name pruinosa is taken from the Latin word pruina meaning covered in hoar-frost, referring to the waxy covering on the foliage and inflorescence.In 2000, Lawrie Johnson and Ken Hill described two subspecies in the journal Telopea and the names have been accepted by the Australian Plant Census:
Eucalyptus pruinosa Schauer subsp. pruinosa;
Eucalyptus pruinosa subsp. tenuata L.A.S.Johnson & K.D.Hill 2000 has smaller buds and fruit, and finer pedicels than subspecies pruinosa.
